-- Sub-Sahara Africa Stocks: Air Mauritius, Equity Bank of Kenya
-- B y   C h r i s   K a y
-- 2012-06-13T15:50:07Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2012-06-13/sub-sahara-africa-stocks-air-mauritius-dangote-sugar-nigeria.html
Namibia’s  FTSE/Namibia Overall Index (FTN098) 
climbed for a second day, increasing 0.4 percent to 897.32 in
Windhoek.  Kenya ’s  All-Share Index (NSEASI)  rose 0.1 percent to 64.94 in
Nairobi. The Nigerian Stock Exchange All-Share Index declined
0.1 percent to 21,210.58 in Lagos, according to data compiled by
Bloomberg. Mauritius’s  SEMDEX Index (SEMDEX)  gained less than 0.1 percent
to 1,790.40 in Port Louis.  Air Mauritius Ltd. (AML)  , sub-Saharan Africa’s fourth-
biggest airline, dropped 3.6 percent to 10.7 rupees, the lowest
in three years, after posting a 29.6 million euro ($37 million)
loss in the 12 months through March 2012, compared with a profit
of 10.75 million euros a year earlier.  Equity Bank Ltd. (EQBNK)  , Kenya’s biggest lender by
customers, advanced 2.5 percent to 20.75 shillings, the biggest
jump on a closing basis since April 25.  “It is actually a foreign investor who has bought the bulk
of the shares,” George Bodo, a Nairobi-based independent equity
strategist, said in a phone interview today, referring to Equity
Bank. “The current valuations are very attractive.”  Equity Bank trades at 7.4 times reported earnings, compared
with 8.7 for  Barclays Bank of Kenya Ltd. (BCBL)  and 8.9 for  Standard
Chartered Bank Kenya Ltd. (SCBL) , according to data compiled by
Bloomberg.  To contact the reporter on this story:
